The government wants to stop the torture of "witches" and issued a brochure
Women who are labeled witches in Burkina Faso usually have some common social characteristics.
They are more likely to belong to the older generation, they find no work - for example, for health reasons, they are single and have no children.
When one of these women "becomes" a witch, she becomes strictly isolated so that she cannot become dangerous to the rest of the village.
“Men are rarely affected by this fate.”
“Young and healthy women are spared this as they help at work and give birth to children,” one religious sister describes the situation in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso in a specialty home for more than one hundred women who have been expelled from their communities.
The local government now decided to take action against this abnormal "social measure".
And for this reason, a brochure was issued to stop the “witch hunting”.
But there's a catch.
"More than 70 percent of all adults in Burkina Faso can't read," the newspaper "The Standard" pointed to the dilemma of written enlightenment.
To be accused of witchcraft is also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, neighboring Burkina Faso, 27-year-old Ammy Hemmahová was tortured to death by three women and two men - they poured her petroleum and just set her on fire.
This incident was reported by the BBC server, among others.
The perpetrators, however, claimed that the matter was only a coincidence of unfortunate circumstances.
According to her version, oil is inflamed, which is used for ritual anointing.
This is after the group tried to "eject" an evil spirit from the woman.
The isolation of “witches” supports the people here without regard to their education.
The standard quoted a 42-year-old entrepreneur from Burkina Faso as saying: “Eaters of human souls are a danger earlier than they are today,” he said.
While the government in Burkina Faso is at least trying to defuse the witch hunt, last year the Gambian president has properly interfered with the president himself.
"President Yahya Jammeh sparked a monstrous witch hunt after his aunt's death, as they allegedly participated in their deaths and would now try to kill the president himself by black magic."
“For this purpose, he called on shamans from nearby Guinea to help, who, accompanied by police officers, soldiers and the president’s bodyguard, indiscriminately kidnapped women and men from Gambian villages and brought them to the president’s farm in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
On the farm, the incarcerated people were forced to drink an abduction from plants with a hallucinogenic effect, which also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the people arrested did not survive the stay on the farm.
Only due to international pressure were the nearly one thousand prisoners released.
A tenant of Bakala: He heats in the oven - but still pays higher rent
An elderly man is leaving the RPG Byty client centre of the coal baron Zdenák Bakala, the largest private owner of rental apartments in the Czech Republic.
Under the arm a folder with three new leases for three apartments: for the own and the apartments of his daughters and his son, who is currently serving a prison sentence.
All three have just been raised as part of the so-called "deregulation".
Instead of a monthly rent of 3,500 crowns, the son is expected to pay 4100 crowns for a 2-bedroom apartment with kitchen of the second category next year.
"And there isn't even running hot water in the apartment and you have to heat in a simple coal stove," he taps annoyed with his finger on the son's new lease, for whose signing he has a power of attorney.
"But what - I signed," he explains half-depressed and half resigned.
BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "incorrect and immoral," advises tenants not to sign the new contracts and wait until December 7th, when it intends to publish a guide on how to proceed against such contracts.
But the man just waves off.
“One says this, the other says that,” he makes a dark face.
The region of Ostrava thus becomes a large "deregulation laboratory".
After the New Year, this deregulation is imminent for most rental apartments in the Czech Republic, whose tenants do not yet pay a market-friendly rent.
Aktuáln.cz therefore decided to visit this "lab" in person.
The RPG waiting room in Havázov is one of four in the Ostrava region and already nine in the morning this Tuesday is breaking full.
Right next to the door are the bodyguards of a security agency and a caller.
"Rent 2011", so a special touchpad lights up on the touchscreen.
Taped briefly and the device is already spewing out a number sheet.
We have hardly deciphered the number "157" and it is already beeping on the large display on the ceiling of the waiting room.
Half a second later, it’s your turn.
A little later, an older couple enters the waiting room to ask about the rent, but the onslaught in the waiting room apparently does not apply to the new rent.
Most people are here to solve the usual problems - repair requests, insurance issues and the like.
From mid-November onwards, the envelopes in the Ostrava region with the new rental contracts will flutter into the mailboxes of most of the RPG’s total of 44,000 apartments.
The RPG Byty proposes a rent increase of about 15 to 38 percent in the letter.
The special counter for the new rentals in the client centre has been open since 18 November.
“The action is going on a little over a week, that is, that’s just the beginning,” the ladies behind the counter reply after a moment of hesitation when the “client” turns out to be a journalist.
The deregulation and Bakala’s former miners’ homes are a hot topic.
Prior to the elections, Ostrava-based parliamentary vice-president Lubomir Zaorálek of the SSD had taken up this issue quite loudly, no wonder the newspapers are full of it today.
“Twenty years I want a new floor from them.”
"Not even a besch. WC glasses they could change," the man mentioned at the beginning airs up.
So far, according to the employees, pensioners in particular are at the counter to convince themselves whether they really receive the promised rent reduction, which promises them RPG, if they sign the special offer in time.
The other tenants, who sign the new lease by 15 December, will also benefit from a half-discounted February rent.
So far, however, "deregulation switches" in Havzov are anything but overloaded with demand.
"Of yesterday's 360 clients, only about 40 to 50 of the rentals were here in 2011," the counter officials estimate.
RPG offers individual rental agreements on its websites as well as wall panels where it seems necessary.
However, if the rental parties do not agree on the new rent, it will be determined by an independent court.
“This should not be a threat, but should be understood as information about the only possible and completely legitimate legal approach,” RPG explains on its websites.
“No one goes to court here,” says one of RPG Byty’s employees and a man on the street in front of the client centre, at least in part.
“I have 13,000 (crowns) pension, of which I have 5,000 left for food, where should I get the money for a court dispute,” he says.
Then the employee becomes insecure.
"Let's see."
“Mr. Zaorálek tells them about the media not to sign and so people are still waiting,” she says.
The regulated rent ends with the New Year 2011 in most of the Czech Republic and according to RPG Byty, the rent increase is an economic necessity.
"The existing amount of rents is not even enough to maintain the housing fund," argues Pavel Klime, director of the RPG Byty housing portfolio, and - in the opinion of the homeowners, the neglect of the housing fund criticized by the tenants is the main reason for the rent increase.
While RPG was able to invest four billion in the apartments in the years between 2005 and 2010, in the four years from 2011 to 2014 it is expected to be 5.2 billion.
On the large-format LCD display on the ceiling opposite the upholstery chairs in the waiting room of Havov, a few red glowing information appear in between.
"The rental increases in 2011 by 15% and less affect 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG's apartments."
"Always this means a maximum of 7.50 CZK per square meter per month", you can read on the LCD monitor.
Only with 400 apartments from RPG’s portfolio, the rent increases by 38 percent.
"In these cases, it is about raising extremely low rental prices of CZK 19.66 per square metre," argues RPG.
With 2600 apartments, the rent remains at the same level next year.
RPG Byty promises that the deregulation will not increase rents abruptly, but will take place gradually within four and eight years.
What's more - the company imposes another obligation: All revenue from the rental increase (see diagram) the company wants to put back in the apartments, especially in heat savings - in new windows and in thermal insulation.
But - above all, these should benefit those who sign the agreements on the rent increase.
The architects saw - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini kindergarten here, with everything that belongs to it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to Arch.Design employees since last year.
Design and architecture firm Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of well-known Brno buildings come, calculated from the first designs for the new building Avriopoint with the premises for its company mini kindergarten.
In a wise foresight, because most of his 90 employees (in) are in the baby boom age and the company is concerned that the project architects return to their workplace as soon as possible.
Along with the possibility to work shorter, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of their social program.
This makes it easier for the civil engineers to combine their demanding profession and childcare.
The mini kindergarten is an original idea of the employees of Arch.Design and with the support of the management they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The small kindergarten is financed by the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment Policy from the European Social Fund and from the national budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this funding (CZK 2.8 million grants), the necessary facilities and equipment were procured and qualified personnel and operations were provided for the duration of 2 years.
After the funding has been used up for 2 years, Arch.Design is obliged to continue operating the mini kindergarten for 3 more years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the company providing active assistance in processing the application.
For the children, full-time qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can attend children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini kindergarten, only 5 children can be present at the same time, but the day alternates with several children.
The kindergarten is flexibly adapted to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights with regard to the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is individual education and care, the program content in mini kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the framework program of preschool education.
The children not only play here, but above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to preschool lessons, they also learn English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer that is available to the children.
What's more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
Parents can take a look at the children at any time and thus the stress is eliminated when the children are picked up late from a far away kindergarten.
Parents therefore use their working hours more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships are also developing here.
Arch.Design thus ranked among the Czech companies, which offer significant benefits in the recruitment of new employees, which are family-friendly and strengthen their personnel marketing through such programs.
A bone house fascinates even after 100 years. Check out the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn-up fish mole.
This is the Casa Batlló of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms was nicknamed "bone house".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile fragments and mosaics, the shed-like facades and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of Antonio Gaudi’s Art Nouveau style.
The facade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and living things.
It is only on closer inspection that one notices that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and well-thought-out order.
At night, the whole facade looks even more plastic, dramatic and the special lighting enhances the shine of the colors.
The same sweeping lines and twisted shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-like shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, ornamental elements of doors, even holes and strips.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was created by the renovation of a house from 1877, which was executed by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on demolishing the old and building a completely new building, but ultimately agreed to Gaudi’s idea of an unusual and also cheaper reconstruction.
However, the rental house Casa Batlló did not design Antoni Gaudi alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
Especially on his drawing board were the decorations for the representative apartment of the reality owner and also the use of mosaics on the facade was his idea.
However, numerous other designers and artists also contributed to the design of the facade.
The joint work on the designs for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudi.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudi's Casa Milá in the Güell Park, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudi.
Shortly after its completion, the house was nicknamed "bone house" by the local residents of its organic forms.
Others, in turn, called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "gagging house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of St. George, the patron of Catalonia.
But also other sculptural elements symbolize hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi designed a central heating system for the house, which was unique at the time, with vent channels and typical fireplaces.
Somewhat bizarre her 45-degree inclination already.
In his work, Gaudi consistently ignored all the building regulations of the time and was not distracted by them.
Before construction began, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that the city fathers were so horrified at the completion two years later that they demanded remedy.
Among other things, the councillors also encountered the fact that the construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, changes were no longer made, quite the contrary - just fifteen days after the district's request to do so, Josep Batlló filed a request to authorize the rental of the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The homeowner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor was a social salon, on the third floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewellery store.
The entire six-storey building goes through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the conversion eliminated all right angles and straight lines and replaced them with curved and curved walls.
Gaudi also worked with a modern concept for the interconnection of spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and so a larger society could chat comfortably without having to give up some intimacy during more confidential conversations.
The house was given a rather unusual roof and two more floors by Gaudi’s remodeling in addition to a new facade.
Gaudi’s play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is dressed and the light courtyards are also impressive.
The play of these two colors gives a maximum of light to all floors of the house.
In doing so, he simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb the sunlight.
House Casa Batlló, which was added to the UNESCO World Heritage list in 2005, can now be visited by anyone.
On the first floor is the most spacious and magnificent apartment made available to the public.
The homeowners decided to take this step only in the year and on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When one found that this was a quite profitable business, one kept the visits, yes, one expanded them to further common and the attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for visiting the monument is not a cardboard handle, it is 16.50 euros, students, retirees, groups and holders of tourist ID cards receive a 20% discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudi buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon turrets, you should try to make friends with one of the householders and visit him at home.
The right mattress and the right bed grate? Women have different desires than men
Not the best bed frame, but the quality of the lying surface - so mattress and rust make up the good bed.
However, these must complement each other harmoniously in order to meet the wishes of the specific user.
Many things play a role in the selection - the weight, the size, the state of health and last but not least the sex of the sleeper.
Equally important is the interior in which the mattress and rust have to be subordinated.
Typical example?
In a weekend house that is not heated regularly, latex mattresses are not well suited, as they take much longer to "get warm".
In addition, they are significantly heavier than conventional polyurethane mattresses.
And - they should be reversed regularly.
If they do not have enough venting ducts in the core and lie on a solid plate, moisture builds up: It is therefore not excluded that mold forms underneath them.
Of course, when it comes to choosing, it also plays a role in what you are used to.
If you have been abroad for a long time, where very high mattresses with soft layer are common, it will be difficult to get used to a low mattress with a hard surface.
"All the hockey players who came back from the NHL have complained to me that they can't sleep right here."
"For their skinned shoulders, heels and hips they just need a soft layer of visco-foam (Memory Foam - a shape memory polymer)."
"I also recommend these, among other things, to people with diabetes who suffer from a nervous system disorder, so that they can not receive the "information" from the joints and skin," explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
That’s why I bought many ice hockey players years ago, but also other customers, these mattresses with visco-foam (memory foam).
"Today this is no longer a problem, because such mattresses offer, among others, the manufacturer Tempur, the Italian company Magniflex or the Czech manufacturer Tropico."
And you don’t necessarily have to be a famous ice hockey player to appreciate the benefits of visco foam.
This “miracle” actually works quite simply.
The foam optimizes its hardness and shape according to the absorbed heat, in other words, it directly clings to the warm body.
Nowhere does it squeeze, at night you don’t roll around like after a heavy fight.
You just sleep much better.
The viscoelastic foam also offers protection against decubitus (burn).
When choosing the mattress size, you should still add the length of the soles of the foot, i.e. about 21 to 34 cm.
Man and woman, who are 180 cm tall, need a 210 to 220 cm long bed.
Each of the sleepers should have at least 90 cm of lying width available, i.e. together 180 cm.
For single beds, for example for singles, 120 to 140 cm are attached.
For convenience and also for possible visitors.
Otherwise, the following rule of thumb applies to the ideal bed width: "If you lie on your back, there should still be enough space for the slightly angled arms", advises Ing. Helena Prokopová, the guild master of the upholsterers and room furnishers, who has been devoting herself to the problem of healthy sleep and ergonomics of furniture for years and presents this topic also in technical schools.
With a double bed, everyone needs their own grate and mattress, but be careful when shopping, so that the mattresses are equally high.
Otherwise, there is nothing left but to mount the grate at different heights and this is far from possible with every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, mattresses with feather skeleton 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters should be accounted for on the molding layer and the fine cushion.
"You should not feel the feathers by hand or when you sit down," warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a special rust type.
Fully padded beds with mattress and undercarriage such as co-grown Siamese twins have nothing to look for in the bedroom.
These mattresses cannot be ventilated and the cover cannot be washed, which is already common today.
And since you lose between 0.2 to 0.75 l of sweat in a single night, it is clear that after five to seven years, the mattress slowly becomes a giant (and clogged sieve).
This is also why experts reject advertising slogans that promise a lifetime of up to 25 years, even a lifetime warranty, for mattresses.
Every thing has its if and but.
And therefore a practical advice from the dealers: For mattresses of 120 or 140 cm width, you should not shy away from the hygiene of the washable, detachable covers, yet it is advisable to use a mattress protector, which you can easily take off and wash.
Even though today mattress covers are usually made with a circular zipper, so that you get two halves after opening (important for the washing process and the washing machine size!), the manipulation with larger mattresses, especially on your own, often resembles the unequal fight between David and Goliath.
Do they have a solid plate in bed instead of a rust?
Get out of here!
Or at most for a bed for unloved guests and for a single night.
Also, they should rather provide the plate with ventilation holes (if there are none in it) and use mattresses with feather skeleton and 15 cm minimum height with so-called pocket spring core and fine cushion.
Polyurethane mattresses do not belong on such a base.
Latex or sandwich mattresses are suitable (possibly combinations of latex and coconut) for non-adjustable slatted slatted slats with 14 to 18 spring slats (lamellas), with lattice support in the lumbar vertebra area and the possibility of regulating the lattice hardness.
Adjustable slatted grids do not include mattresses with a feather skeleton, as they do not respond to the ergonomic adjustment.
In addition to the adjustment of the stiffness of the spring strips, special flexible shoulder modules are also offered.
This involves a special fastening of the spring strips, which allows the spring strips to be pressed in or even bent in such a way that they allow the shoulder of the sleeper to sink at points.
Especially for men with wide shoulders an important thing.
There are even mattress manufacturers who have started using soft zones for the shoulder area in "man's mattresses".
The ladies are also thought of - they are given these soft zones in the hip area.
For the most demanding customers, point-elastic vane spring systems (lattoflex) or grids with point-elastic contact pads with so-called multitorsion suspension are designed.
The pressure is distributed over several points, which reduces the voltage.
But - if you use a bad (too large and full) pillow for the right mattress and rust, most of the benefits are lost again.
Here again a rule of thumb: the pillow should support the head, its tips should only reach up to the shoulders so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
Ideally, therefore, a 50 x 60 cm cushion, as the Scandinavians, for example, like it.
In the side position, the pillow (along with the shoulder relief zone in the rust or the soft zone in the mattress) should compensate the shoulder height.
Our modern mattresses have something in common with the former straw bags (filled with hay).
Modern manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least their admixtures.
Also for mattresses, the new magic word is called "bio".
Instead of petroleum raw materials, natural oils are increasingly used for the production of polyurethane foams - for example castor and soybean oil.
Soybean is used by all known manufacturers.
"Organic means mattresses, which are made of materials of purely natural origin," explains Petr Va'ek from Tropico Plus.
Natural materials are also used in the production of mattress covers - one of the first was aloe vera.
However, you can also indulge in microcapsules that spread fresh forest or lavender scent when you sleep.
There is also a difference between man and woman.
While in men, a "cooling" plant extract from birch leaves is used so that the mattress cover can absorb the heat and cool the body, the covers have "warming" effect for women.
Extracts from red peppers stimulate the blood circulation, so the weaker sex gets comfortable warm when sleeping.
And today's favorites?
Cold foam mattresses (it has larger pores with destroyed cell structure and is therefore more breathable than commercially available polyurethane and also much more flexible).
The combination of the different stiffnesses of cold foams and visco-foams creates multi-zone mattresses that know exactly where the head, hip and heels are.
For a high-quality mattress, however, you have 7000 crowns and more.
However, health mattresses are usually subject to lower VAT, as they are considered medical aids.
Gumotex was the first Czech company to receive this advantage.
You see, saving on the mattress and the rust is not so easy.
Occasionally, there are special offers from manufacturers and retailers that offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers the mattress Duofreeze with visco-foamed memory for 11,990 CZK.
The second one is free of charge.
It was the material Tempur that initiated the era of viscoelastic foams with an open cell structure and high density at an almost cosmic pace.
No wonder they were developed for NASA, because the astronauts are exposed to enormous overloads at the launches.
Tempur becomes soft in heat, in a cool environment it solidifies again.
In this way, it adapts perfectly to the human body and distributes the body pressure in an optimal way.
It is therefore not only ideal for preventing compressive fire, but generally increases sleep comfort.
However, viscoelastic foams are used not only in mattresses, but also in other health products, such as special foot pads, which are intended to provide relief to the legs and vessels.
Local manufacturers use, for example, the foams Eucatherm C, Twinsaver or similar products.
More and more parents want human surveillance devices to keep the kids under control
Anxiety about your own children is growing and so more and more parents are considering monitoring them via GPS.
The system, which was originally invented to find cars, can locate people just as well, which would be helpful in such cases as the recent traceless disappearance of nine-year-old Aniska Janatková.
The device is currently about the size of a cigarette box, but soon it should not be larger than a wristwatch.
Many people have been terrified by the case of the missing Aniska, so they are looking for ways to better protect their children.
Also for the price of impairing your privacy.
“We strive to tell everyone that this is not about spying around, but about an effective means of reducing the likelihood of tragedy,” says Petr Pilin of the company Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of GPS tracking devices on the Czech market.
“I admit that in individual cases there may be abuse of such devices, for example, if you put it in someone’s pocket without them knowing about it, but we haven’t had such a case yet.”
“Most customers really buy it for safety reasons,” Pilin adds.
In his opinion, however, the child should always know what purpose the "box" serves and how to use it in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Boáková points out, however, that if a child does not like to wear such a thing, he simply gets rid of it.
“Even very young children show great creativity when it comes to deliberately losing certain things if they don’t want to be controlled.”
"At first, the mobile phones raised great expectations from the parents, but they can be switched off just as easily as these new surveillance devices," says Ms. Boáková.
In their opinion, it is also controversial whether such an institution actually helps in the event of an attack.
"In the case of planned kidnappings, the kidnapper virtually always checks whether the child has any electronics to locate it with."
“Today it’s the phone.”
"If such surveillance devices were to be used more widely, they would also be looking for them, as their sale would certainly be accompanied by massive advertising."
“In these cases, the criminals are always one step ahead of the police,” says the psychologist.
However, she acknowledges that similar devices can be quite helpful in the event of a sudden attack by a pedophile.
