A longer index finger than ring finger means a lower risk of developing cancer
Men whose index fingers are longer than the ring finger are obviously at lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published by the British Journal of Cancer on Wednesday.
This is because it is related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our findings show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially in men up to sixty,” said Ros Eeles, a professor at the University of Warwick’s Cancer Research Institute.
The finger could help determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health burdens, Ms. Eeles added.
From 1994 to 2009, she and her colleagues in Britain tracked more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3,000 healthy men.
In more than half of the participants in the study, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men, the same probability of prostate cancer applied as for 19 percent of those men whose ring and index fingers were the same length.
However, in men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk fell by 33 percent, in men up to sixty even by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned, which form at prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that it is precisely the testosterone that accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
The leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, Václav Pacees, said he was briefly aware of this study, but he did not yet consider the relationship between finger length and cancer risk to be "completely proven".
