The Democratic Routine
The democracy movement in Latin America is getting stronger, as is the support of private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, the influence of Brazil is greater than that of the United States.
These findings came from the Latinobarómetro survey, conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been conducted on a regular basis since 1995 and thus shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly striking in this year’s September and October survey.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and second, the growing interest in democracy and its most important institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased sharply (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown by about 6% annually since 2002, the number of proponents of democracy rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Even in Mexico, where the economy has been recovering since last year’s sharp downturn, such a trend can be seen.
However, only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see chart 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with their country’s democratic practice, which is as much as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Diagram 3).
Approximately 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% trust their government, both of which correspond to last year’s, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America’s economic crises undermined efforts for more democracy.
This may be due to the fact that the countries of Latin America experienced only a short period of recession and quickly recovered.
In addition, the poor were accommodated by a stronger social network.
(According to reports from the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only slightly in 2009 and fell by 32% this year.)
However, there are strong mood differences from country to country (see chart 4).
Brazil’s strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva are reflected in a widespread thought of progress.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more noticeable and violent crimes have increased, this is less the case.
It is only for the second time since the start of the survey that many respondents in Latin America see a greater problem in crime in their country than in unemployment (see chart 5).
Approximately 31% say that either they or a family member were victims of a crime last year, but compared to 38% last year, the values have fallen, reaching the lowest level since 1995.
The increase in economic performance is reflected in the increased support of the private and market economies: about 71% of respondents across the region indicated that the private sector was indispensable for development, compared with 56% in 2007 (see diagram 6).
Approximately 58% said that only the market economy can bring progress to their country, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have maintained this view (and 80% are for a private sector), although their left-wing president, Hugo Chávez, nationalizes many private companies.
