Arsenic-resistant microbe could enable new forms of life on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of an alien bacterial species that can live on arsenic, among other things, opens up new possibilities for new forms of life on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, it is a sign that life is possible even without the elements previously considered vital.
“This organism has two options.”
"He needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow."
"This makes it very special, although it's almost a kind of 'foreign' life form," said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which will appear Thursday in the online issue of the journal Science.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital – carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But as the scientists found out, the bacterium in Mono Lake in California continues to grow even when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
“You’re wondering what else is possible,” said Ariel D. Anbar, co-author of the Arizona State University report.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists need to recognize life and its forms, according to Anbar.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference in which no details of the discovery were disclosed gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could be about the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that in other planetary systems, organisms can initiate biochemical processes with the help of other elements and that the 'standard elements', which we believe are absolutely vital, are not necessarily fixed," said Charles Cockell, professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute at the Open University of Milton Keynes in the United Kingdom.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novelty because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures, one element can be replaced by another," Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon from NASA’s Astrobiological Institute, who led the study, chose the Mono Lake due to its high arsenic content.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, she assumed that microbes exposed to both could potentially replace one element with the other.
"The toxicity of arsenic is mainly due to the fact that it behaves chemically similar to phosphorus."
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another."
"But the difference is so big that arsenic works differently than phosphorus, it gets into our biochemical system, where it smears almost everything," Anbar explains.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing concentration of arsenic.
The microbe grows better in phosphorus, but that it can also survive in arsenic shows that an arsenic-based lifeform can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon on which arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, a lecturer in microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new, but so far there hasn’t been a working example.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, which is why science assumed that early life forms used it.
"This gives reason to believe that life may have evolved differently than it did in the early Earth Age," said Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
