Can politeness connect the breakup?
After a campaign of infamy and negativity, little politeness broke out in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of genuine two-party cooperation or a moment of illusion before one quickly returns to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and Congressional leaders did not bring a breakthrough in the big issues that were addressed during the so-called “lame duck session,” the session at the end of a period of government in which decisions are no longer taken.
After all you hear, it was not a polite discussion between two different sides or a respect for their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of a partisan point-gathering.
The public meeting of the President’s Deficit Commission on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences that persist between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months creates mutual respect that obscures the ideological divide that continues to separate members.
This is hardly enough to say that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a test phase - in which one of the other signs of willingness to cooperate and compromise is demanded, while one tries to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of the voters after a renewed party warfare.
Therefore, the meeting on Tuesday itself and its assessment by the participants were limited to a minimum of claims or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it is about taxes, donations, health or expectations, the two sides are miles away from each other.
Last but not least, the November elections in Washington voted mildly for at least a short time.
“No question, the tone has changed,” said Pete Wehner, an official representative of the Bush administration, who is now working for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
“This is inevitable after the elections.
Elections evoke partisan passions that die again.
And that's good."
On some issues, especially those on the agenda of the “lame duck session,” Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts end at the end of the year, and no one supports that.
Both sides want to find a way to get some or all, be it temporary or permanent.
Similarly, a compromise on increased unemployment benefits is to be expected, if only because Republicans cannot afford to believe the favored tax cuts for the rich while denying support to unemployed workers.
After the meeting on Tuesday in the White House, the optimism has increased that one can agree on these issues during the "lame duck session" and at the same time ratify the New START Treaty.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on urgent issues of the lame duck session does not necessarily lead to permanent cooperation between the parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
“After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation,” he said.
Wehner is also skeptical - and this skepticism is shared by many - that politeness leads to true cooperation.
“I see a lot of what is happening from today until 2012, as a pre-fight, or shadow boxing, for the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the presentation of the new Republican majority in the White House and with the tea party voters who have served their formation.
As concerned as Republican leaders may be that they are playing poker too high, they know they must try to keep their promises to cut government spending and override health reform.
These party lines are already evident in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the Deficit Commission, which include tax reform and raising some taxes, as well as raising the retirement age and lowering government spending.
Vice-Chairman Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own estimation, have pushed so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes within the Commission to make their plan the official recommendation and they are struggling very hard to get even close to that number.
The greatest resistance can be found in the elected representatives of the panel, as there is little room for compromise in financial matters, at least today.
Galston predicts two phases in the fight between the White House and Republicans in Congress.
The first battle will take place next year in the form of party clashes when Republicans challenge Obama on the state budget, taxation, and health care system, followed later by a phase of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
Public opinion.
It is proven that, despite the partisanship of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to a dead end, as it did in 1995, then both parties must pay close attention to the public response.
Whoever is condemned to lose will have to change course and seek compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Particularity and polarization are bigger today than in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a larger ideological divide between Obama and Congressional Republicans than they were between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a far more far-reaching election in 2012.
From this point of view, the courtesy displayed this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find a common denominator in the questions that continue to separate the two.
