On the one hand, José Luis Rodriguez Zapatero has presented new adjustment measures, from tax reductions for small and micro-enterprises, the regulation of temporary employment companies, the lifting of the €426 support for unemployed people who do not receive unemployment benefits, to the privatization of 49 percent of AENA, the administration of Barajas and El Prat airports, and 30 percent of the state lottery.
On the other hand, Deputy Prime Minister Elena Salgado, with the help of former Prime Minister Felipe González, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as responsible, who has summoned the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It should be anticipated that Merkel’s position is not a mistake of her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany takes a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which conflicts with the preservation of the traditional traditions of most of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: A strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: The reintroduction of the German mark - although this currently sounds more like science fiction - supported by a large part of the public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a change in the euro according to German proposals. This means: more macroeconomic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of the countries that violate the requirements; the possible suspension of payments in some countries and the extension of the costs of potential adaptation measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been showing up for some time, so there are no excuses now.
At first, in 2009, both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government pulled a constitutional reform out of its sleeve to prevent this from 2016.
This was the first indication of the divergence between what Germany considered necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign set the Central European country when Merkel painfully delayed the decision to save Greece.
This was strongly criticised at the time, but the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public and the public opinion were absolutely against saving Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel comes out with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union’s agreements in order to enable the rescue of a country and at the same time to oblige private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position was construed as anti-European because it pushed the Irish crisis and all the following.
But their proposal, although sweetened, has been adopted, and in the coming months we will be participating in the reform of the European Union, which will enable these measures from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that does not intend to cross it.
It tells everyone that - even if unpopular measures have to be taken now - from this date onwards the old functioning of the euro will no longer exist.
2013 will be the birth year of a new currency area in which the violating countries can be severely punished, forced to declare themselves insolvent, and in which case the private sector will have to bear part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we need to take a hard course of growth, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improvement in productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as it was led by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would be bad at not understanding it.
It is not just about reducing the government deficit to 3% by 2013.
The demands are much tougher.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is cheat ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will turn into more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities we are offered by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero has understood this as well, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the discussion with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures yesterday) points out that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in her own home has prepared its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn’t seem that something would change.
Among the possibilities that have been considered is that we would have to leave the euro area, which is full of less reputable countries.
In this case, Germany could still tell us it had warned us.
Sport and circumvention
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The supposedly instigated exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against the Ajax in the Champions League resulted in a lot of ink being shed on whether it was an unsportsmanlike act or not and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is generally known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead his group, the two players will meet the prescribed penalty in the next league match against the Auxerre and thus enter the next phase without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the club’s coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card in such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten but followed rules in this sport.
Part of the debate about the case presented goes back to the fact that a team of football club Real Madrid (who in his anthem showed nobility and honor and on other occasions punished his players for similar incidents) played the lead role in the game, and to the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history than a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate is about whether this behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the statutes, contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether these actions constitute a rule-bypass; in fact, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
In this case, the damage caused to the sporting spirit should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to prevent the offending players from taking an unjustified advantage from the counter-team.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we normally mean by cheating or bypassing rules, because the circumvention of the rule has not been carried out in secret to avoid a penalty, but it should be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
The players waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders pulled out of the intentional foul.
It should be pointed out that the rival was not placed in a less favourable position, nor were advantages for the game being played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term, to a certain extent uncertain advantage, as the team could eventually also leave. In addition, with this procedure, players receive a penalty and move into the second card cycle, in which they leave because of card accumulation with a card less than in the first cycle.
It is not so clear whether this is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such approaches are not directed against the sporting spirit, which includes strategic decisions in order to take the greatest possible benefit from the regulations.
In this case, players didn’t want to circumvent a sanction (that would actually be a clear case of rule-bypass), they were more likely to choose when to undergo it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding or escaping a punishment.
Although the line between inventiveness and rule environment is blurred, I believe this matter is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that the polemic has arisen as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked rule transmission.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than aesthetic.
Offer-Offensive for Group Christmas Dinner in Barcelona
The dictatorship of the calendar drops an avalanche of reservations this year on the days of 16 and 17 December.
The celebrations paid by employees themselves are spreading. They do not want to spend more than 20 to 30 euros.
Like the Turrón and the Christmas lottery, during the pre-Christmas season, there are also group dinners that supply oxygen to the restaurant and leisure industry in Barcelona, but as a result of the economic crisis, they trigger a price offensive to capture the customer segment, which is the big crowd: Almost everyone wants to spend between 20 and 30 euros for lunch or dinner, the surveyed entrepreneurs and associations confirm.
To make accounting a bit more complicated, the calendar (New Year's Eve falls on a Friday) dropped all orders into the week of December 13, resulting in an avalanche of dinner reservations on two peak days (the 16th and 17th) and almost no orders the week before.
Since 2008, when the bad times began, many companies have discontinued group dinners for household reasons.
In order not to have to give up this tradition, many workers pay it out of their own pocket.
Whatever the economic situation, low prices are demanded, confirms the chairman of the Barcelona Hospitality Board, Gaietá Farrás.
The representative of the umbrella association has not yet dared to predict what the holidays will look like this month.
"People think about it dozens of times before reserving."
“They want to go out, but they pay a lot of attention to the prices,” he emphasizes.
The business will go well with those who "offer quality at good prices with a good service," he adds, reminding us that customers will save in times of crisis, which is why prices are demanded the most by 25 euros.
In a survey in several centrally located restaurants it turns out that the evening of December 17th leads the providers to collapse.
The Soteras Group says that the demand for this Friday with the intention of spending less than 30 euros would boom. The Group has adjusted its menus with complete offers between 25 and 35 euros to the economic situation.
