In some companies you can also see green sprouts sprouting, which is why the employees are invited again. This gives the impression that the group meals are back in recovery.
On the side of the umbrella association Fecasarm (with associations such as the Bar, Restaurant and Leisure Association of Barcelona), the vice-chairman, Enric Gomá, trusts to see the end of the tunnel and notes that the reservations are quite "lively" overall, although the customers "do a maximum."
The fun of the party did not go down, no matter who paid.
Pakistan’s nuclear program raises major concerns in the United States
Islamabad makes nuclear weapons “faster than any other country.”
Wikileaks revelations confirm Taliban-Pakistan relations.
The content of the correspondence between the North American embassy in Pakistan and the U.S. Department of State revealed by the internet portal Wikileaks confirms the enormous concerns that the Pakistani nuclear program Washington is raising.
On the fringe of the clarifying and juicy details provided by the documents on the content of the talks and the mindset of the accredited North American diplomats in Islamabad, they reveal that cooperation between the two countries in matters of nuclear security is not strengthened, but rather “decreases”, and that the unstable Asian country produces more nuclear weapons “to a faster rhythm than any other country.”
In particular, the peculiarity of Pakistan's nuclear program -- that the weapons are not assembled, but their parts are stored to make their destruction more difficult in the event of a possible attack -- is preparing sleepless nights for Washington.
In a report before the visit of former head of the National Security Council, James Jones, ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson said: “The proximity of some nuclear facilities to the area attacked by the Taliban, the presumed dispersion of nuclear material and the vulnerability of transporting nuclear material.”
The large number of people involved in the nuclear arsenals and missile programs is no longer only seen by the US, but also by Russia as outrageous and reason to exercise caution.
“Pakistan needs to hire strictly religious personnel to guard nuclear facilities; due to the low level of education and culture, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people who work on nuclear or missile programs,” Russian Foreign Ministry expert Yuri Korolev said in a meeting with his North American counterparts.
New to the documentary unveiled by Julian Assange’s Internet portal is that cooperation between the US and Pakistan on nuclear proliferation is declining and the increased pace at which Pakistan produces nuclear weapons.
In May, an embassy office describing communications with Pakistan as “frustrative” said: “Often there is no transparency; we don’t get answers or they are rejected.”
In another message, Peter Lavoy, a state intelligence official for South Asia, acknowledges that “despite the economic catastrophe, Pakistan is producing nuclear weapons as quickly as no other country.”
Ambassador Patterson asks Washington during a visit of Chief of the Army, General Ashfaq Kayani, to “clarify to the person in charge that “Pakistan’s army has to stop its tacit support of terrorist groups.”
Hunting for WikiLeaks boss
Obama appoints a senior leader in the anti-terrorism struggle to prevent new revelations.
Interpol gives a red warning about the pursuit and discovery of Assange.
Everything related to WikiLeaks and its founder, Jullian Assange, forms a complicated labyrinth in which the issues are difficult to clarify.
Yesterday, Interpol issued a “red warning” on “finding and persecuting” Assange.
However, this is not a traditional arrest order.
It’s not new, it’s from November 20.
It also has nothing to do with the last revelation of over four million U.S. diplomatic documents, but with the allegations of sexual abuse that the Australian has to face in Sweden.
WikiLeaks’ lawyer Mark Stephens said: “The police knew where and how to contact Mr. Assange.”
Already on the 20th, the international police agency based in Lyon (France) issued the order at the request of Sweden, but it was not announced until yesterday after receiving the power by the Swedish authorities.
The 188 Interpol countries are instructed to identify and find Assange "in order to temporarily arrest and extradite him."
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red warning, many member countries, according to the organization, view the red warning as a license for arrest – which must be carried out by the national police – especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case with Sweden and England, where Assange is presumably staying.
The move upset Assange’s lawyers, who posted a letter informing them that the 39-year-old founder of Wikileaks is ready to answer the questions of the Swedish authorities via videoconference.
They also recall that Assange applied for the exit from Sweden and received the appropriate permission from the prosecutor, who is compared to the legendary Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, Stalin’s chief of security.
“This is like a hunt, not a legal prosecution,” the letter said.
As the world searches for him - and his mother from Australia affirms her son's innocence - Assange stays in an unknown place, but not silently.
On Monday, he interviewed the head of Time magazine via Skype from an indefinite location, requesting the resignation of U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
“If it can be proven that she was responsible for ordering North American diplomats to spy on the UN and thus violated international agreements signed by the US, she would have to resign,” he said.
His opinion was condemned yesterday by White House press secretary Robert Gibbs, who described the request for resignation as “ridiculous and absurd.”
“I’m not sure why we should value the opinion of a guy with a website,” he told CNN.
Obama himself has commissioned a high-ranking anti-terrorism leader, Rusell Travers, to prevent new document disclosures.
President Barack Obama’s attempt to pay less attention to Assange is contrary to the opinions expressed by conservative politicians and commentators these days.
Congressman Peter King, who will chair the House National Security Committee from January, has called on the State Department to investigate the possibility of putting Wikileaks on the list of terrorist organizations “to seize their funds and pursue anyone who supports or contributes to them.”
Tom Flanagan, adviser to Canadian President Stephen Harper, had gone even further, and he had to revoke his statement that Assange had to be “murdered.”
“Obama would have to turn it into a target and use an unmanned plane or something.”
Who didn’t apologize was Mike Huckabee, Baptist minister, former governor of Arkansas and potential presidential candidate.
“Whoever it was that leaked information into the government is guilty of treason and anything that is not execution is a mild punishment,” he told Fox.
Puigcercós seeks peace in the ERC with a wink to the Carod
The Republican leader allows the party to secretly vote on its continued existence in office.
Huguet proposes a more pluralistic government and the end of the General Assembly principle.
Joan Puigcercós seems to have found a recipe to avoid for the tenth time an internal turmoil in the ranks of the directionless ERC after the loss of 11 MPs and half of the electoral votes.
The party leader is aware that his resignation threat is not enough for former party leader Josep Llu’s Carod-Rovira, but he also knows that the influence of this sector is as weak today as its mentor itself and will not cause him the same headaches as other former currents.
Therefore, the leader of Esquerra tries with a wink to win the new critics, which would secure his position until the next local elections.
Earlier today, the ERC’s over 200 regional councillors announced that they could secretly comment on his stay in office.
With ballots, not with a raised hand.
If the Carodists wanted to miss out on the presidency, they could do so without fear of reprisals.
In fact, the boss wants to avoid both the impression of division and that of submission to his person.
In several interviews, he affirmed that he would feel unconfirmed with half of the votes plus one, and he added, without specifying percentages, a result "in the Bulgarian style" would not be good either.
Carod's supporters demand more from the president than just making his office available to the party, an insufficient gesture, since Puigcercós controls the supreme body of congresses.
But since they do not have a sufficient majority to force resignations, they will agree with the board on a plan of action from now until May.
To this end, they expect to be able to participate in the preparation of the Strategic Reorientation Document, which will be submitted to the Council for a vote on the 18th.
Their intention is to guarantee Puigcercós, which in return promises to move Congress to autumn 2011, which the party leaders already consider a fact.
The president of the ERC believes that the "polyphony" damages stability and he strives once and for all to enable the organization to wash its dirty laundry behind closed doors.
In this sense, the article that the current conseller Josep Huguet signed on his blog is symptomatic.
Given that Puigcercós is an ideologue, the owner of Innovació considered it a fact that the party leader was supported "in exchange for different goals".
He counted five, two of which are in the foreground.
First, the "restructuring" of the board, so that it represents at least 90 percent of the party members, that is, the inclusion of new faces from Carod's environment.
The second could be the big news.
Huguet suggests that ERC should finally abandon the general assembly principle as a way of functioning.
In doing so, he advocates a reform of the statutes, which should allow the congresses to be held with elected delegates.
Puigcercós' team, who fought for it at the last two congresses, is obsessed with the end of the general assembly model - an exception in the Spanish party system.
In fact, at the 2008 quake assembly, the party leadership was tasked with reviewing the general assembly principle at a congress to deal with the reform of the statutes.
This date is yet to come, as infogle was not advisable for the internal upheaval of recent years to address this matter.
Now, without the critical sectors lurking, the time may have come to take up this matter again and to conclude it forever.
