China maintains its targets to reduce greenhouse gases
China’s representative at COP16 said his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and would maintain its offer to cut 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China keeps its offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, Su Wei, the country’s representative at COP16, reassures.
At his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations Climate Change Summit (COP16), Su Wei said his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and transform its industry.
He stated that over the past four years, his country has invested $245 million to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
On the other hand, he stated that China would not change its goals, but would work together with the international community on this matter.
He explained that China’s climate change strategy is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building, and support for pilot programmes.
Progress has been made in all aspects, including the adoption of a new energy law last year, which includes the targets for reducing gas emissions, he said.
On the other hand, he emphasized that in China, the authorities of the states had worked with those of the central state and the municipalities to achieve the goals of energy saving, effective use of energy and reduction of emissions.
In addition, he has carried out, initiated or completed several multi-year plans, both those financed by the Chinese government and those that received funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the Energy Efficient Usage Program, which has been introduced over the past five years and has received investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and privately held.
A provincial project on climate change is also underway, another for exchanging traditional light bulbs with energy-saving bulbs and another for mitigation and adaptation, he explained.
Martin Krol, a scientific government adviser on climate change in this country, confirmed that China’s efforts are far greater than would be commonly believed.
He pointed out that the per capita greenhouse gas emissions in China are six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons. China is responsible for a nine percent total contribution to pollution.
It is also making unprecedented progress in the field of energy use. Energy efficiency has increased by 20 percent in the last five years and another is expected to happen by 2020, he explained.
