Obama campaigns on Twitter for the law in favor of undocumented students
“If you’re in favour of passing the Dream Act, then call your senators and urge them to pass that law,” the president tweeted on the popular social network.
President Barack Obama today backed the nationwide mobilization in support of the Dream Act – law legalizing undocumented students with a message on his personal blog on the social network Twitter.
“If you’re in favour of passing the Dream Act, then call your senators and urge them to pass that law,” Obama tweeted.
His brief contains a cyberlink to a more comprehensive document that urges the public to contact their senators, including as the vote of the law is imminent.
“With your voice we’re waiting for, the time has come to listen to you,” he emphasizes.
The news was spread after the 42 Republican senators threatened to block all votes for any law unless the extension of tax cuts from the Bush era and government funding would be extended.
Such a blockade announced on a letter signed by the 42 Republican senators could affect the vote on the Dream Act and other projects such as the ratification of the new START agreement with Russia against the proliferation of nuclear weapons.
Asked about the Republican blockade of the Dream Act and other projects, Presidential Spokesman Robert Gibbs said he trusts that once the tax issue is resolved, a timetable can be drawn up for the rest of the projects.
"I think we still have a lot of time..."
“We all agree that the tax issue must be settled by the end of the year.”
“I believe we can make an agreement on this at any time and then we can plan the rest,” he said.
Senate Democratic Majority Chairman Harry Reid announced Tuesday that he would “apply for the vote at the end of the debate” so that the Dream Act, which would allow the initiative to legalize undocumented students, could be voted in Senate starting next Thursday, although next week would be more likely.
The version of the Dream Act, or the Law of the American Dream, would legalize about 800,000 young people who immigrated to the United States when they were under sixteen years old, living in that country for the last five years, enrolled in a higher education institution or in the army.
But the advocates of the law need sixty votes to pass the initiative, which is why they rely on the votes of a handful of Republicans. Currently, the organizations of the advocates of this project are organizing an intense influence on the passing of the law.
The Democrats, the majority of whom support the Dream Act, have 58 seats.
However, one of them, Senator Ben Nelson of Nebraska, said he would vote against it and only one Republican, Richard Lugar of Indiana, has announced his support for the law.
Therefore, the defenders of the Dream Act must get several Republicans on their side if other Democrats decide to turn their backs on the initiative.
Among the most enlisted Republicans are Maine, Olympia Snowe, and Susan Collins, as well as Florida Senator George Lemieux, who took over the mandate of Senator Mel Martinez.
Other Republicans who supported the Dream Act in the past include Utah-based Orrin Hatch and Texas-based Kay Bailey Hutchinson, but they said they would not support it on another occasion.
Another Republican who supported the law, John McCain, has not yet defined his position.
Although the House of Representatives has a different version, analysts agree that the Dream Act in the Senate is facing the biggest obstacles.
