The second round of 'The Pleasure of Language' was a walk where the participants made their way to the narrative
"I understand that with sex in language, but ... the finger in the wound? What is expected of me?" asked the writer Luisa Valenzuela, who was to open the second round of 'Los placeres de la lengua', a cycle that celebrated Spanish-language literature and on this occasion used the subtitle of her question (at another event, she explained the round table was dedicated to sex in language).
The finger in the wound... "brings us into trouble," the Argentine writer spit sweetly towards the audience, which was mainly composed of young people who gathered at the International Book Fair in Guadalajara (FIL) to attend this round table moderated by Marisol Shultz, in which Valenzuela, Sergio Ramirez, Mayra Montero and Luis Garc participated.
Luisa Valenzuela read a text she dedicated to Gonzalo Celorio, which Shultz then described as a great story. Luisa tells in the first person and is the protagonist who is looking to learn what a "wound" is, and goes from doctor to doctor, of which she does not answer, but receives clues for the guide of her story.
She leaves the infectologist convinced: "Patience is not my strength, maybe that is my wound."
Finally, after a frustrating approach to the traumatologist, who took her breath in the middle of the corridor, but who explained to her that wound was not a scientific concept, the psychoanalyst reveals the secret: "The wound is the really open, the symbolic is the scar."
The main character of the narrative sighs relieved and concludes that she "only learned of the wound that it is really open and does not exist", but she is convinced that the pleasure in the language and its traps are mixing.
Valenzuela, the writer, played with both of them.
The Nicaraguan Sergio Ramirez also presented an adorable narrative, which he called 'praise of the invention', in which the finger in the wound is not mentioned, but is discovered.
With allusions to magical realism, he tells of a famous sorceress who touched the clouds, brought back far-traveled men, or restored the virtue lost by a girl. The narrative made a turning point and told of America, the great novel, which from the beginning was not lacking in his own chroniclers, and he critiqued Bernal Diaz del Castillo, who told the stories of the prosperous.
Cervantes, who invited us all (the writers), mocked the fake witnesses who appeared in the stories portrayed as true, but otherwise the story of America would never have been told – with imagination that even the sense of shame was lost.
However, he emphasizes, "it is the madmen and liars who imagine things best," and there reality and lie approach each other, where one no longer knows which side the narrative belongs to, where fictional literature reaches the summit.
He actually calls it the “Tradition Cervantes.”
“We inherited from him what is being told.”
When it was Mayra Montero’s turn, the writer commented on and praised the variety of interpretations to which the FIL’s invitation to the Round Table “The Finger in the Wound” had contributed.
The Cuban and Puerto Rican woman dedicated her contribution to the great wound of social violence that affects her country -- like all of Latin America -- as a result of the struggles for drug trafficking.
“I believe that good literature, good poetry, good songs contain a tacit, not intentionally planned engagement,” she explained, after highlighting that literature is communication and commitment that builds up between the author and readers as if it were a “chemical reaction.”
The evening was concluded by the Spanish poet Luis Garcia Montero, whose contribution also included "this finger of the committed writer in the writer's wound".
He noted that in a fast-paced world, intellectual habits and the control of consciousness also result in dogmatisms, forgetting that “behind every confirmation there is a little ‘no’ and behind every denial a little ‘yes’.”
"To be in possession of our thoughts and of reality, we must nuance: and nuances often mean to put your finger in the wound and to harass those who feel much more comfortable when they think in the form of cartoons, in black and white, in prefabricated ideas without nuances, and also to harass the powerful who prefer to reappear the world in black and white.
