The U.S. changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Before their interview with the consulate, the persons must present themselves to the visa application services; the costs will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa will change at the Embassy of the United States and in the consulates.
In the case of the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves in the consulate at the visa application services (ASC, the initial letters in English) before their interview.
The staff of the ASC shall record the biometric data of the applicant, which shall be verified by the consulate prior to the interview.
The new process has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa is reduced because it is no longer necessary to pay separately for the appointment, processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed over.
The applicant only makes a single payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the counterpart to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for traders and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa do not have to have a conversation in the consulate, they only have to introduce themselves to the nearest ASC, where they present their documents and their fingerprints are taken.
Since the biometric data is collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second date for the conversation remain in the consulate there less time than before.
Those who apply for the visa in the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the service fee of $26.
Further information on the new visa application procedure can be found on the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
NASA announces the discovery of extraterrestrial life
The North American space agency called a press conference to present tomorrow a find that will have an impact on the search for living things in space.
The United States National Aerospace Agency (NASA) is announcing an astrobiological discovery tomorrow, Thursday, that could confirm the theory of the existence of extraterrestrial life.
The finding will be presented tomorrow at a press conference in the NASA headquarters in Washington by astrobiology experts, a science that explores the origin, development, distribution and future of life in the universe.
When the press conference was convened, NASA assured that it would present “an oversight finding for the search for extraterrestrial life,” prompting speculation among experts from other countries.
The discovery could prove the theory that in hostile environments that were previously considered uninhabitable, human-like creatures could exist. The hypothesis has been raised that they could turn into intelligent living beings -- like humans -- if their living conditions improved.
Apparently, it is a microbe found on the bottom of Mono Lake in Yosemite National Park, California, where it lives in an environment considered too toxic for all conceivable forms of life, as the lake is heavily arsenic.
In some way, the microbie uses arsenic as a survival resource. Taking this ability into account, the chances are increasing that there may be similar life on other planets that do not have our protective atmosphere.
When these organisms metabolize arsenic, according to the astrobiologists, "there is actually a different form of life, a second form of life that is different from what we know."
The space agency will announce the actual reach of its findings at the press conference tomorrow, Thursday.
The conference will be attended by geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who is investigating the possibility of life on Mars, and biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists who studies Titan (Saturn's largest moon) on the question of whether its chemical composition resembles Earth.
