On Wednesday, ten searches were carried out in the Estrie administrative region as part of the dismantling of a production and sales network of cannabis.
Fourteen people were arrested and will face various charges.
The house searches took place in Sherbrooke, Orford, and Stoke, at the sites that were said to have served predominantly for drug production.
“About 750 cannabis plants, four kilos of hashish, cash and equipment that served the production have been confiscated,” said Louis-Philippe Ruel, spokesman for the Quebec Security Police.
Eleven men and three women were arrested, two of whom are from Sherbrooke.
The detainees are said to have appeared in front of the Sherbrooke courthouse hours after their arrest.
They could be accused of, among other things, the production of cannabis, its possessions for sales purposes, the conspiracy, and the service of crimes.
These house searches had taken place as a result of a lengthy investigation activity that went on for over a year.
“The information obtained from the public has allowed us to carry out these arrests,” said Ruel.
Around 70 police officers from the regional investigative unit Estrien of the Quebec Security Police, the Sherbrooke Police Service and the Memphrémagog Police Department had participated in this police operation.
