Rivers under strict supervision
Several rivers remain under strict surveillance due to the high rainfall that has occurred in some regions of the province since Tuesday.
In Shawinigan, in the administrative region of Mauricie, a landslide occurred on Wednesday afternoon.
Two houses were evacuated.
In the evening, another landslide occurred in Saint-Lin-Laurentides, in the administrative region of Lanaudere.
A road has sunk in itself.
From Tuesday to Wednesday evening, heavy rainfall from 40 to 70 milliliters has rained on several regions.
Between 20 and 40 more millimetres of precipitation were expected here by Thursday evening, according to the regions.
The areas north of the river and the Outaouais Valley were most affected.
A total of up to 100 millimeters of rain showers had fallen here.
Since the snow melt, which has already accumulated in certain sub-areas, is to be added to these precipitations, the crossing of several watercourses is feared.
On Wednesday evening, the Quebec Security Service issued warnings about the flood alarm regarding the Ouareau and Achigan rivers in the Lanaudere region.
The rivers in the north, in Saint-Jérome, in the Laurentian Mountains and the Chêne in Lotbinière become the object of flood monitoring and continue to be observed.
In the Lanaudière region, the heavy rainfall has resulted in the crossing of some lakes in Sainte-Julienne, Sainte-Marcelline-de-Kildare as well as in Rawdon.
In Saint-Calixte, an escape bridge was torn away due to heavy rainfall.
Ten residences had to be evacuated as a preventive measure.
In Outaouais, crossing certain lakes has caused the closure of several roads, especially in the municipality of Mansfield-et-Pontefract.
The security service remains on alert and closely monitors the situation, security adviser Annik Bouchard said.
The Quebec State Flood Centre, for its part, issued warnings on Wednesday of the strong rise of several rivers, in particular of Maskinongé, Assomption, Ouareau, Achigan, Batiscan and Loup.
