Instead, moderators should provide sound as misleading information.
On the subject of suicide, presenter Stéphane Dupont had argued that suicide was an expression of cowardice.
The majority of the Supervisory Board members had concluded that the message conveyed was that suicide should not be seen as a solution to life crises.
“The majority of the Supervisory Board considers that the consequences of the Dupont le midi program would have addressed a sensitive issue in a family-friendly and appropriate manner.”
Therefore, he was not reproached for his person.
The last issue involved the statements relating to the earthquake in Haiti.
Stéphane Dupont and Jean-René Dufort had a media-driven dispute in this regard, which had provoked a lot of reactions.
The CHOI moderator had declared that he did not donate in favor of Haiti aid, since one would not know for sure whether the needy would actually receive the donations.
The Supervisory Board believes that these comments were not abusive, but that their cumulative effect presents an unjustified negative representation of Haitians.
"I have already dropped my three-day suspension penalty in this matter."
“My file has been virgin for a year and a half,” the moderator said.
In all decisions, the Supervisory Board denounces the proliferation of a rude form of expression.
In all cases, the CHOI-FM broadcaster acted "beyond its obligations".
The consequences for the broadcaster, who, among other things, had to communicate his decisions once during the main broadcasting period within a period of three days, are minor.
