Global Plan for Renewing Lighting
Yesterday in Cancun, the UN proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gases (GHG), which corresponds to nearly a third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments from developed countries.
According to the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem in the form of 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of CFCs released to the earth due to lighting would be avoided if the white-hot bulbs, which still represent a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or better still, light-emitting diodes (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is equivalent to 70% of the global fleet’s exhaust gases.
Last year, in Copenhagen, major exhaust emissions emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global CFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
From this balance sheet, however, 5 Gt would have to be deducted in order to stabilize the climate increase by 2 degrees Celsius from today to the year 2020 in order to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white glowing pears, 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produces the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced again by twofold.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last on average between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week – this company has participated in the UN study by the way – have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-hot bulb, giving an indication of the savings of the exchange plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that completely novel light bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a control resistor.
And they do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and that they therefore have to be disposed of as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless the producers provide a pickup point.
However, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet, according to the report, is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit significantly more mercury to generate the electricity wasted by the white-glowing bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report sets out in detail the profits that each country would generate thanks to this international program.
Indonesia, for example, would save one billion dollars annually on the purchase of electricity and eight million tons of CO2, an equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants, the construction of which would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
