Climate: How France Makes Its Financial Promises Beautiful
One year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to examine compliance with the fast-track financing pledges (also called "fast-start" or premature financing) that have been realized by developing countries.
And now the rough French fairy tales have been uncovered.
Under the Copenhagen Treaty, developing countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has pledged 7.2 billion euros over three years, France 1.26 billion euros (i.e. 420 million euros per year).
On the occasion of the opening of COP16, the EU drew all the registers to convince its partners of their commitment to fast-start financing: detailed action report from its Member States, press conference, major side events, brochure distribution.
Operation Transparency is remarkable and appreciated for its true value: developing countries and civil society would like to see all developed countries do the same at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released 2.2 billion euros in 2010, which puts it on the right track to pay respect for its commitment of 7.2 billion euros in 2012.
But when you look into the details, things are a little more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Treaty, this money should be "new and additional" to ensure that an additional effort has been made without detrimental to public development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what “new and additional” means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain member states, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the guideline that he considers best.
For example, the European Commission has chosen to be the benchmark for 2009: international financing will be maintained and 150 million euros will be added over three years as part of the funding.
Other countries have adopted similar guidelines, either in terms of year or in terms of conditions at the level of public development assistance.
In return, France felt that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 was "new and additional".
In other words, there are no benchmarks in the expenditure of the previous year or at the global level of public development assistance.
In concrete terms, the total amount of French aid to developing countries can remain stable (or decrease) - France pretends to comply with its commitment regarding "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule about this, and everyone chooses their calculation mode.
Some, such as France, find 1 borrowed € equivalent to 1 donated €.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often linked to emission control projects based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is deceptive to present the euro, which is taken as the equivalent of a donated euro... In addition, only the cost of the loan to the investor country should be counted as commitment (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing but the following consideration: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by taking 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5% 36.1 million euros) - see also the EU document to convince itself of this.
France is the only country in the EU to make large loans.
Germany calls for 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (among other countries) are 100% committed to making donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to meet their obligations, France only gives 10 cents and understands a similar commitment.
Nice hocus pocus!
All in all, in its fast-start financing, France operates with a double hoax: in part with a further development of the action over time and in the other part with the reality of the financial commitment.
France manages to make it believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" million in line with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (as it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative effect; once within the EU (why do the other member states continue to donate, if it is enough to lend?) and then in the negotiations, as the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The chapter of early financing is only a small question for a relatively short time compared to the totality of discussions about the climate.
But it could be the drop too much in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
However, it is indispensable to learn its lesson from this first year of early financing.
In the first place, France could announce a change in its bookkeeping style for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and balancing justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, however, France could bring forward the discussions on the subject of long-term financing (another, crucial and currently debated topic): one cannot escape the question of "calculability" or the type of accounting of his loans.
France could change its position to be just as progressive in terms of disputes as it is in other things.
The hope is therefore based on the new Minister of Environment Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about France’s fast-start and its vision of “reliability” and the use of loans would naturally raise the international trust base necessary for further discussions.
